# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iso-20022
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The message metadata is described by UML models with a special ISO 20022 UML Profile.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] Underlying all of this is the ISO 20022 metamodel – a model of the models.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The UML profile is the metamodel transformed into UML.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The metadata is transformed into the syntax of messages used in financial networks.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The first syntax supported for messages was XML Schema.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] ISO 20022 is widely used in financial services.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] ISO 20022 is the successor to ISO 15022; originally ISO 20022 was called ISO 15022 2nd Edition.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] ISO 15022 was the successor of ISO 7775.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] ISO 20022 Financial services – Universal financial industry message scheme.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] A 2015 report by the United States's Federal Reserve System classified Europe having "mature adopters" of ISO 20022; India, South Africa, Japan, Singapore, and Switzerland as having "growing adopters"; and Australia, Canada, the United Kingdom, and New Zealand as having "interested adopters".
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The report concluded that the Federal Reserve should push for ISO 20022 adoption within the United States financial system.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] Australia's New Payments Platform, launched in February 2018, uses ISO 20022 messaging.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The Reserve Bank of New Zealand plans to support ISO 20022 from November 2022 onward.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] Nordic countries launched the P27 payment platform, but that initiative eventually failed in 2023.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The Eurosystem in March 2023 switched its real-time gross settlement to T2, which follows ISO 20022.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The switch involves transactions for settling payments related to the Eurosystem's monetary policy operations, as well as bank‑to‑bank and commercial transactions.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] TARGET2 previously handled transactions for over 2000 G€ per day.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] In the United States, the Federal Reserve's Fedwire Funds Service will begin using the ISO 20022 messaging format in July 2025.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The Federal Reserve's FedNow instant payments service also uses ISO 20022 messaging.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] The private Clearing House Payments Company's RTP instant payments service uses ISO 20022 messaging.
[src:iso-20022/iso-20022] Its CHIPS funds transfer service migrated to using ISO 20022 in April 2024.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] A **payment system** is any system used to settle financial transactions through the transfer of monetary value.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This includes the institutions, payment instruments such as payment cards, people, rules, procedures, standards, and technologies that make its exchange possible.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] A payment system is an operational network which links bank accounts and provides for monetary exchange using bank deposits.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Some payment systems also include credit mechanisms, which are essentially a different aspect of payment.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Payment systems are used in lieu of tendering cash in domestic and international transactions.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This consists of a major service provided by banks and other financial institutions.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Traditional payment systems include negotiable instruments such as drafts (e.g., cheques) and documentary credits such as letters of credit.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] With the advent of computers and electronic communications, many alternative electronic payment systems have emerged.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] The term **electronic payment** refers to a payment made from one bank account to another using electronic methods and forgoing the direct intervention of bank employees.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Narrowly defined electronic payment refers to e-commerce—a payment for buying and selling goods or services offered through the Internet, or broadly to any type of electronic funds transfer.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Modern payment systems use cash-substitutes as compared to traditional payment systems.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This includes debit cards, credit cards, electronic funds transfers, direct credits, direct debits, internet banking, e-commerce payment systems and Buy now, pay later (BNPL).
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] More recently, protocol-level payment mechanisms have emerged as alternatives to account-based models.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] The x402 open standard repurposes the HTTP 402 "Payment Required" status code to enable payments directly within the HTTP request–response cycle, eliminating the need for user accounts, sessions, or traditional payment intermediaries.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Payment systems may be physical or electronic and each has its own procedures and protocols.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Standardization has allowed some of these systems and networks to grow to a global scale, but there are still many country-specific and product-specific systems.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Examples of payment systems that have become globally available are credit card and automated teller machine (ATM) networks.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Additionally, forms exist to transfer funds between financial institutions.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Domestically this is accomplished by using Automated clearing house (ACH) and real-time gross settlement (RTGS) systems.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Internationally this is accomplished by correspondent banking (possibly using the SWIFT network) or a more centralised system like the CLS settlement system.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] An efficient national payment system reduces the cost of exchanging goods, services, and assets.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] It is indispensable to the functioning of the interbank, money, and capital markets.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] A weak payment system may severely drag on the stability and developmental capacity of a national economy.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Such failures can result in inefficient use of financial resources, inequitable risk-sharing among agents, actual losses for participants, and loss of confidence in the financial system and in the very use of money.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] The technical efficiency of the payment system is important for the development of the economy.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] An automated clearing house (ACH) system processes transactions in batches, storing, and transmitting them in groups.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] An ACH is considered a net settlement system, which means settlement may be delayed.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This poses what is known as settlement risk.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Real-time gross settlement systems (RTGS) are funds transfer systems where the transfer of money or securities takes place from one bank to another on a "real-time" and on "gross" basis.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Settlement in "real time" means that payment transaction does not require any waiting period.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] The transactions are settled as soon as they are processed.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] "Gross settlement" means the transaction is settled on one to one basis without bunching or netting with any other transaction.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Once processed, payments are final and irrevocable.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Comparatively, ACHs are typically used for low-value, non-urgent transactions while RTGS systems are typically used for high-value, urgent transactions.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Countries and regions have also implemented real-time or instant (or faster) payment systems which typically operate 24x7x365 and perform the transaction from debit of ordering customer's account to credit of beneficiary customer's account within a timeframe of 10–15 seconds.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] International payment systems operate like their domestic counterparts but have additional complexity as they need to navigate currency exchange and cross-border jurisdictional and financial environments.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] The key system used for international transfer has been the SWIFT network that is used by banks to transfer funds between countries.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] International transfers have traditionally been cumbersome, error prone and expensive.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Increasing globalization has driving corporations and individuals to transact more frequently across borders.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Transaction volume continue to increase with people buying from foreign eCommerce sites as well as traveling, living, and working abroad.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] For the payments industry, the result is higher volumes of payments—in terms of both currency value and number of transactions.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This is also leading to a consequent shift downwards in the average value of these payments.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Payments systems set up decades ago might be retrofitted or force-fitted to meet modern business needs.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Frequently, the systems become unstable or less reliable, for example, STEP2 (an upgrade from 2003), which processes only euros.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This has led to new transfer services that use financial technology or cryptocurrency to make it easier, faster and cheaper to transfer funds internationally.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] As of 2014, STEP2 is the only Pan-European automated clearing house (or PE-ACH system) in operation.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] This type of system is thought to become less relevant as banks will settle their transactions via multiple clearing houses rather than using one central clearing house.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] T2 is a RTGS system that covers the European Union member states which use the euro.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] It is part of the Eurosystem, which comprises the European Central Bank and the national central banks of those countries that have adopted the euro.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] T2 is used for the settlement of central bank operations, large-value Euro interbank transfers as well as other euro payments.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] It provides real-time financial transfers, debt settlement at central banks which is immediate and irreversible.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] For users of these systems, on both the paying and receiving sides, it can be difficult and time-consuming to learn how to use cross-border payment tools, and how to set up processes to make optimal use of them.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] Solution providers (both banks and non-banks) also face challenges cobbling together old systems to meet new demands.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] For these providers, cross-border payments are both lucrative (especially given foreign exchange conversion revenue) and rewarding, in terms of the overall financial relationship created with the end customer.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] The challenges for global payments are not simply those resulting from volume increases.
[src:iso-20022/payment-system] A number of economic, political, and technical factors are changing the types of cross-border transactions conducted.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] As of 1985, three central banks implemented RTGS systems, while by the end of 2005, RTGS systems had been implemented by 90 central banks.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The first system that had the attributes of an RTGS system was the US Fedwire system which was launched in 1970.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] This was based on a previous method of transferring funds electronically between US federal reserve banks via telegraph.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The United Kingdom and France both independently developed RTGS type systems in 1984.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The UK system was developed by the Bankers' Clearing House in February 1984 and was called CHAPS.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The French system was called SAGITTAIRE.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] A number of other developed countries launched systems over the next few years.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] These systems were diverse in operation and technology, being country-specific as they were usually based upon previous processes and procedures used in each country.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] In the 1990s international finance organizations emphasized the importance of large-value funds transfer systems which banks use to settle interbank transfers for their own account as well as for their customers as a key part of a country's financial market infrastructure.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] By 1997 a number of countries, inside as well as outside the Group of Ten, had introduced real-time gross settlement systems for large-value funds transfers.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Nearly all G-10 countries had plans to have RTGS systems in operation in the course of 1997 and many other countries were also considering introducing such systems.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] RTGS systems are usually operated by a country's central bank as it is seen as critical infrastructure for a country's economy.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Economists believe that an efficient national payment system reduces the cost of exchanging goods and services, and is indispensable to the functioning of the interbank, money, and capital markets.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] RTGS system does not require any physical exchange of money; the central bank makes adjustments in the electronic accounts of Bank A and Bank B, reducing the balance in Bank A’s account by the amount in question and increasing the balance of Bank B’s account by the same amount.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The RTGS system is suited for low-volume, high-value transactions.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] It lowers settlement risk, besides giving an accurate picture of an institution’s account at any point in time.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The objective of RTGS systems by central banks throughout the world is to minimize risk in high-value electronic payment settlement systems.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] In an RTGS system, transactions are settled across accounts held at a central bank on a continuous gross basis.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The settlement is immediate, final, and irrevocable.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Credit risks due to settlement lags are eliminated.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The best RTGS national payment systems cover up to 95% of high-value transactions within the national monetary market.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] RTGS systems are an alternative to systems of settling transactions at the end of the day, also known as the net settlement system, such as the BACS system in the United Kingdom.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] In a net settlement system, all the inter-institution transactions during the day are accumulated, and at the end of the day, the central bank adjusts the accounts of the institutions by the net amounts of these transactions.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] The World Bank has been paying increasing attention to payment system development as a key component of the financial infrastructure of a country and has provided various forms of assistance to over 100 countries.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Most of the RTGS systems in place are secure and have been designed around international standards and best practices.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] There are several reasons for central banks to adopt RTGS.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] First, a decision to adopt is influenced by competitive pressure from the global financial markets.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Second, it is more beneficial to adopt an RTGS system for the central bank when this allows access to a broad system of other countries' RTGS systems.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Third, it is very likely that the knowledge acquired through experiences with RTGS systems spills over to other central banks and helps them make their adoption decision.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] Fourth, central banks do not necessarily have to install and develop RTGS themselves.
[src:iso-20022/real-time-gross-settlement] In 2010, the World Bank published a report on payment systems worldwide, which investigated these countries' usage of real-time gross settlement systems for large-value payments.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The **Single Euro Payments Area** (**SEPA**) is a payment integration initiative of the European Union for simplification of bank transfers denominated in euros.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] As of 2025, there were 41 members in SEPA, consisting of the 27 member states of the European Union, the four member states of the European Free Trade Association (Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway and Switzerland), the United Kingdom, as well as five EU candidate countries.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Some microstates participate in the technical schemes: Andorra, Monaco, San Marino, and Vatican City.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] As of 2025, Albania, Moldova, Montenegro, North Macedonia and Serbia are the five countries negotiating to join the EU that are included in SEPA.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA covers predominantly normal bank transfers.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Payment methods which have additional optional features or services, such as mobile phone or smart card payment systems, are not directly covered.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] However, the instant SEPA payment scheme facilitates payment products also on smart devices.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The aim of SEPA as stated in 2008 was to improve the efficiency of cross-border payments and turn the previously fragmented national markets for euro payments into a single domestic one.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA would enable customers to make cashless euro payments to any account located anywhere in the area, using a single bank account and a single set of payment instruments.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] People who have a bank account in a eurozone country can use it to receive salaries and make payments all over the eurozone, for example when they take a job in a new country.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The project includes the development of common financial instruments, standards, procedures, and infrastructure to enable economies of scale.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] As of 2007, it was estimated this could reduce the overall cost to the European economy of moving capital around the region by up to 2–3% of total GDP).
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA does not cover payments in currencies other than the euro.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] This means that domestic payments in SEPA countries not using the euro will continue to use local schemes, but cross-border payments will use SEPA and the euro with eurozone countries to a high degree.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The Nordic countries (other than Finland) do not use the euro and have no plans to adopt the euro.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] These four countries (Sweden, Denmark, Norway, and Iceland) started initiatives during 2017–2019 for simpler, faster, and cheaper cross-border payments between one another.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] These initiatives have however not been successful.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The different functionalities provided by SEPA are divided into separate payment schemes.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA Credit Transfer (*SCT*) allows for the transfer of funds from one bank account to another.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA clearing rules require that payments made before the cutoff point on a working day be credited to the recipient's account by the next working day.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The scheme was introduced in January 2008.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] In February 2014 it replaced the national credit transfer schemes, and later made the use of International Bank Account Number mandatory for transfers.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA Instant Credit Transfer (*SCT Inst*), also called SEPA Instant Payment, provides for instant crediting of a payee, the delay being less than ten seconds, initially, with a maximum of twenty seconds in exceptional circumstances.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] This scheme was launched in November 2017, and was at that time operational for end customers in eight Eurozone countries.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] As of 2024, not all banks offer their customers instant transfers; however, in March 2024 the EU adopted the *Instant Payments Regulation* which requires all banks to offer instant transfers from January 2025 (incoming transfers) / October 2025 (outgoing transfers).
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Direct debit functionality is provided by two separate schemes.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The basic scheme, *Core SDD*, is primarily targeted at consumers and was launched on 2 November 2009.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Banks offering SEPA payments are obliged to participate in this scheme.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] A second scheme, *B2B SDD*, is targeted towards business users.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Banks offering SEPA payments are not obliged to participate in this scheme (participation is optional).
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] All parts of a country are normally part of SEPA.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Jurisdictions using the euro that are not in SEPA: Akrotiri and Dhekelia, French Southern and Antarctic Lands and Kosovo.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Jurisdictions in Europe not formally belonging to SEPA normally use SEPA schemes anyway for international euro payments, especially to or from the eurozone, with exceptions such as fees charged and BIC required.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Several EU applicant states have expressed interest in applying to join SEPA.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Bosnia and Herzegovina intends to file an application sometime in early 2026.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Kosovo intends to apply after passing necessary legislation.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Ukraine as of December 2025 is working on legislation to align Ukrainian law with SEPA standards.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] In February 2026, Turkey was offered membership in SEPA by European Commissioner for Enlargement Marta Kos.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] In July 2026, Turkish Minister of Foreign Affairs Hakan Fidan stated Turkey was interested in joining SEPA and that related financial institutions are working on the issue.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA guarantees that euro payments are received within a guaranteed time, and banks are not allowed to make any deductions of the amount transferred, introduced by a regulation in 2001.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Banks and payment institutions still have the option of charging a credit-transfer fee of their choice for euro transfers if it is charged uniformly to all EEA participants, banks or payment institutions, domestic or foreign.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] This is relevant for countries which do not use the euro; where domestic transfers in euros by consumers are uncommon, and inflated fees for euro transfers might be charged in these states.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Sweden and Denmark have legislated that euro transfers shall be charged the same as transfers in their own currency; which has the effect of giving free euro ATM withdrawals, but charges for ATM withdrawals in other currencies used in the EU.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] In regulation (EC) 924/2009 (the Cross-border Payments Regulation), the European Parliament mandated that charges in respect of cross-border payments in euros (of up to EUR 50,000) between EU member states shall be the same as the charges for corresponding payments within the member state.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] However, the EU Regulation does not apply to all SEPA countries; the most significant difference is the inclusion of Switzerland in SEPA but not the EU.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The rule of the same price applies even if the transaction is sent as an international transaction instead of a SEPA transaction (common before 2008, or if any involved bank does not support SEPA transactions).
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Regulation 924/2009 does not regulate charges for currency conversion so charges for non-euro transactions can still be applied (if not banned by national law).
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] For direct debits, the first milestone was missed due to a delay in the implementation of enabling legislation (the Payment Services Directive or PSD) in the European Parliament.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Direct debits became available in November 2009, which put time pressure on the second milestone.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The European Commission has established the legal foundation through the PSD.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The commercial and technical frameworks for payment instruments were developed by the European Payments Council (EPC), made up of European banks.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] To provide end-to-end automated direct payment processing for SEPA-clearing, the EPC committed to delivering technical validation subsets of ISO 20022.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Whereas bank-to-bank messages (pacs) are mandatory for use, customer-to-bank payment initialization (PAIN) message types are not; however, they are strongly recommended.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Because there is room for interpretation, it is expected that several PAIN specifications will be published in SEPA countries.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Businesses, merchants, consumers and governments are also interested in the development of SEPA.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Since January 2008, banks have been switching customers to the new payment instruments.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] By 2010, the majority were expected to be on the SEPA framework.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] As a result, banks throughout the SEPA area (not just the Eurozone) need to invest in technology with the capacity to support SEPA payment instruments.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] SEPA clearance is based on International Bank Account Numbers (IBAN).
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Domestic euro transactions are routed by IBAN; earlier national-designation schemes were abolished by February 2014 (with delays in some countries), providing uniform access to the new payment instruments.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] Since February 2016 Eurozone payment system users no longer require BIC sorting information for SEPA transactions; it is automatically derived from the IBAN for all banks in the SEPA area.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] An instant 24/7/365 payment scheme named SCT Inst went live on 21 November 2017 allowing instant payment 24 hours a day and 365 days a year.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The participating banks will handle the user interface and security, like for existing SEPA payments, e.g. web sites and mobile apps.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] As of August 2014, 99.4% of credit transfers, 99.9% of direct debit, and 79.2% of card payments have been migrated to SEPA in the euro area.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The official progress report was published in March 2013.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] In October 2010, the European Central Bank published its seventh progress report on SEPA.
[src:iso-20022/single-euro-payments-area] The European Central Bank regards SEPA as an essential element to advance the usability and maturity of the euro.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Different wire transfer systems and operators provide a variety of options relative to the immediacy and finality of settlement and the cost, value, and volume of transactions.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Central bank wire transfer systems, such as the Federal Reserve's Fedwire system in the United States, are more likely to be real-time gross settlement (RTGS) systems, as they provide the quickest availability of funds.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] This is because RTGS systems, such as Fedwire, post each transaction individually and immediately to the electronic accounts of participating banks maintained by the central bank.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Other systems, such as the Clearing House Interbank Payments System (CHIPS), provide net settlement on a periodic basis.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] More immediate settlement systems tend to process higher monetary value time-critical transactions, have higher transaction costs, and have a smaller volume of payments.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] A faster settlement process allows less time for currency fluctuations while money is in transit.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The first widely used service for wire transfers was launched by Western Union in 1872 on its existing telegraph network.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Once a sender had paid money to one telegraph office, the operator could transmit a message and "wire" the money to another office, using passwords and code books to authorize the release of the funds to a recipient at that location.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] By 1877 the service was used to transfer almost $2.5 million each year.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Because the earliest wire transfers were using telegraph networks, it was termed telegraphic transfer and this name is still used in some countries.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The sending bank transmits a message, via a secure system (such as SWIFT or Fedwire), to the receiving bank, requesting that it effect payment according to the instructions given.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The message also includes settlement instructions.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The actual transfer is not instantaneous: funds may take several hours or even days to move from the sender's account to the receiver's account.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Either the banks involved must hold a reciprocal account with each other, or the payment must be sent to a bank with such an account, a correspondent bank, for further benefit to the ultimate recipient.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Banks collect payment for the service from the sender as well as from the recipient.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The sending bank typically collects a fee separate from the funds being transferred, while the receiving bank and intermediary banks through which the transfer travels deduct fees from the money being transferred so that the recipient receives less than what the sender sent.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] For international wire transfers, additional information may be required, such as the recipient’s full name, physical address, bank name and address, bank account number and type, bank routing number, and the bank's SWIFT or IBAN code.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The fees and processing times can vary depending on the service provider and the destination country.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Banks may charge fees for wire transfers.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The exact fees vary widely depending on the type of payment and the type of bank accounts involved.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] In some jurisdictions the fees may be regulated or capped.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Since 2009 the European Union Regulation No 924/2009 controls cross-border payments in the European Union.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] In the new regulation Article 1 (q.v., Ref.4) states that an IBAN/BIC transfer within Single Euro Payments Area (SEPA) must not cost more than a national transfer, no matter which currency is used.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The receiving bank can charge for exchanging to local currency.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] As of 2022, most European banks do not charge private customers for SEPA transfers, apart from possible exchange fees.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] For business accounts, fees may be charged, but usually less than 40 cents.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Prior to this, in 2002 the European Union relegated the regulation of fees a bank may charge for payments in euro between EU member states down to the domestic level, resulting in very low or no fees for electronic transfers within the Eurozone.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] In 2005, Iceland, Liechtenstein, and Norway joined the EU regulation on electronic transfers.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] However, this regulation was superseded by the Single Euro Payments Area (SEPA), consisting of 32 European countries.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] In the United States, domestic wire transfers are governed by Federal Regulation J and by Article 4A of the Uniform Commercial Code.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] In 2016, among the 15 largest retail banks, the average fee for an outgoing domestic wire was $25.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Incoming domestic wire fees were about evenly split between $0 (free) and $15.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Domestic transfers in Australia are generally free to consumers.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] International transfers can be costly, and banks will often charge a fee between $0 (free) and $30, and an FX margin (the difference between the interbank rate, and the rate that you are charged).
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Cheaper alternatives to the banks are available from foreign exchange brokers, who usually charge a lower fee and/or margin.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] With bank-to-bank wire transfer, each account holder must have a proven identity.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Unlike credit card payments, wire transfers can generally not be recalled (though recalls are possible in some cases and jurisdictions).
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Information contained in wires is transmitted securely through encrypted communications methods.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Wire transfers done through cash offices are essentially anonymous and are designed for transfer between persons who trust each other.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] It is unsafe to send money by wire to an unknown person to collect at a cash office; the receiver of the money may, after collecting it, not provide whatever goods or services they promised in return for the payment, but instead simply disappear.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] This scam has been used often, especially in the so-called *419 scams* which often nominate Western Union for collection.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] If a financial institution suspects that funds are being sent from or to one of these entities, it must block the transfer and freeze the funds.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] SWIFT wire transfers are not completely free of vulnerabilities.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Every intermediary bank that handles a wire transaction can take a fee directly out of the wire payload (the assets being transferred) without the account holder's knowledge or consent.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] In many places, there is no legislation or technical means to protect customers from this practice.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Clients are sometimes taken by surprise when less money arrives at bank R.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Contrast this with cheques, where the amount transferred is guaranteed in full, and fees (if there are any) can be charged only at endpoint banks.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] The European Union offers some partial protection from this practice by prohibiting European intermediary banks from taking a fee out of the amount being transferred, even for transatlantic transfers.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] However, it is still common practice for a European brokerage firm to state that they charge no transfer fee, and then contact their bank to take an unpublished fee from the amount transferred as a means to compensate their bank with their clients' assets.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] One of the largest companies that offer wire transfer is Western Union, which allows individuals to transfer or receive money without an account with Western Union or any financial institution.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Concern and controversy about Western Union transfers have increased in recent years, because of the increased monitoring of money-laundering transactions, as well as concern about terrorist groups using the service, particularly in the wake of the September 11, 2001, attacks.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Although Western Union keeps information about senders and receivers, some transactions can be done essentially anonymously, for the receiver is not always required to show identification.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Another option for consumers and businesses transferring money internationally is to use specialised brokerage houses for their international money transfer needs.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Many of these specialised brokerage houses can transfer money at better exchange rates compared to banks, thus saving up to 4%.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] These providers can offer a range of currency exchange products like spot contracts, forward contracts and limit orders.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] However, not all such providers are regulated by appropriate government bodies.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] For example, in the UK, even though such companies are regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority, not all of them fall under FCA scrutiny.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Other such regulators include the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC), the Financial Transactions Reports Analysis Centre of Canada (FINTRAC) in Canada, and the Hong Kong Customs and Excise Department.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Most international transfers are executed through SWIFT, a co-operative society founded in 1974 by seven international banks, which operate a global network to facilitate the transfer of financial messages.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Using these messages, banks can exchange data for the transfer of funds between financial institutions.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] SWIFT's headquarters are in La Hulpe, on the outskirts of Brussels, Belgium.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] SWIFT also acts as an international standards body for the creation and maintenance of financial-messaging standards.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Each financial institution is assigned an ISO 9362 code, also called a *Bank Identifier Code* (*BIC*) or *SWIFT Code*.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] These codes are generally eight characters long.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Using an extended code of 11 digits (if the receiving bank has assigned extended codes to branches or to processing areas) allows the payment to be directed to a specific office.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] For example: DEUTDEFF500 would direct the payment to an office of Deutsche Bank in Bad Homburg.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] SWIFT deviates slightly from the standard, though, by using position nine for a Logical Terminal ID, making its extended codes 12 digits long.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] European banks making transfers within the European Union and within Switzerland also use the International Bank Account Number, or IBAN.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Banks in the United States use SWIFT to send messages to notify banks in other countries that a payment has been made.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Banks use the Fedwire system or CHIPS to actually effect the payment.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Domestic bank-to-bank wire transfers are conducted through Fedwire or CHIPS.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Transmitting and receiving US banks are uniquely identified by their ABA routing transit number.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] Other forms of electronic transfers include, for example, electronic funds transfer system (EFTS).
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] This is the system used to transfer money from a bank account to another party.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] It is also the system used in some payments made via a bank's online bill payment service.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] These transfers are made using a bank routing number and the account number at that institution.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] EFTS transfers differ from wire transfers in important legal ways.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] An EFTS payment is essentially an electronic personal check, whereas a wire transfer is more like an electronic cashier's check.
[src:iso-20022/wire-transfer] EFTS transfers are often called "ACH transfers", because they take place through Automated Clearing Houses.
